text: hi everyone Anthony Fantana here
the Internet's busiest music nerd and
it's time for a review of the new pissed
jeans album honey's pissed jeans is not
only the most surefire way to put the
brakes on a blind date where you're
feeling uncomfortable they're also a
rock band on their fourth full-length
album the majority of this band's
discography is on Sub Pop records
including this new LP and when I
typically listen to a piss jeans album
whether it be their debut from 2005
shallow or hope for men or the album
they dropped in 2009 king of jeans or
this new album as well one single word
comes to mind and that word is finesse
and the reason that word comes to mind
is because this band does not have a
scratch of it I don't even know if
they're interested in having any the
band's singer just wails and gargles his
lyrics kind of like a drunk guy being
held down by three police officers
outside of a trashy nightclub downtown
on a Friday night
most of the band's songs kind of run at
this mid-paced kind of grungy kind of
sludgy tempo that I don't know if they
played any faster they might lose their
composure the band's drumbeats are
typically pretty simple a lot of the
fills spacious but thunderous going off
like gunshots and as far as the guitars
go when they're playing chords they are
just pumping them out with force but the
guitars tend to flail wildly when it
comes to solos and then leads it's just
a range of different ideas from noise
rock sludge metal and post-hardcore
there are moments in this band's
discography that reminds me of early
work from The Melvins
as well as flipper on Seine and when
they get really chaotic and slow most
definitely the Jesus Lizard it's no
secret that the band has been sticking
very passionately to this kind of one
sound and style with very minor
adjustments over the years however that
doesn't keep honey's from feeling just
as real as any of the other band's
albums when it comes to that pissed-off
feeling especially since on this new
wreck
they're still working with Alex Newport
who helped them record their last album
which did display a heavier side of the
band a more direct and kind of cut
through outside of the band now honey's
like usual for pissed jeans is kind of a
crossroads of of different loud rock
ideas and because the band is able to
embrace so many different ideas in loud
rock in one record even though they're
kind of staying within their comfort
zones they're still able to kind of
deliver a pretty versatile set of tracks
like the track bathroom laughter which
kind of kicks the album off which has
this sort of Punk momentum to it it
actually reminds me of one of the
flawless from ceremony's previous album
runner Park the song sick to be specific
except much noisier much more chaotic
it's really a kick-ass way to start off
the album just like they kind of started
off their last LP but it's really a
night and day change when it comes to
tempo and emotion as soon as they jump
into the next track which is chained
worker and the song kicks off with these
blast beats but then quickly dives into
these slow distorted bass riffs that
just move like molasses and it almost in
a way kind of becomes sort of droney
kind of atmospheric the vocals are just
shouting what what feels like something
very rageful hateful there's some
moments where it actually kind of
reminds me of a birthday party except
way less noisy and avant-garde but still
enjoyable all the same though there are
some moments where the vocals do kind of
get laid out with effects that make this
track feel at least a little bit
psychedelic the band feeds into the next
track with this pretty catchy riff but
honestly there's not too much about this
song other than the riff that really
kind of sticks with me unfortunately the
band doesn't hit me again with something
that really kind of sticks in the back
of my head until the track you're
different in person which just has all
these dissonant guitar chords flying at
me from every direction when it comes to
just very sour intervals and then note
combinations this song has that down and
when it comes to speed and just the
vocals being so manic and so wild
this song is just wallowing in its own
emotional filth the song cafeteria food
comes shortly after which I loved off of
this LP
it's a much slower track it's toned down
when it comes to being noisy and intense
but with the lyrics which kind of
reference seeing this person with his
stick figure family on his car sort of
saying weird things about you know him
making healthy choices with this
cafeteria food being sung with these
deadpan vocals it's just kind of an
eerie set of images the narrator of the
track maybe seems kind of disturbed and
this song also kind of runs congruent
with a lot of tracks that they've
written over the years that sort of see
this sickness and mundaneness and
everyday mainstream you know kind of
normal life after this the band just
kind of continues its downward spiral
into Slaven Leacock rock with a lot of
noise and a lot of riffs and even though
I like it especially the raw emotion
especially with the energy honestly
pissed jeans is just not going to
translate for people who like their
songs maybe a little bit more composed
or you know maybe a little more
methodical but really it's all kind of a
matter of degree I mean I think there
are people who are into hardcore punk
but may not necessarily get into just
how freewheeling pissed jeans can be on
a track because really this LP and most
of piss jeans discography is about
letting go it's about getting loose and
about kind of unleashing the Beast which
can be really great for kind of
conjuring this really strong and
ferocious and uncompromising vibe but it
doesn't necessarily always add up to a
memorable musical moment the song health
plan on the latter half of this LP is
absolutely freaking hilarious not only
because its riffs are so pounding but
the lyrics are amazing with shouting out
this mantra that you know you want to
know my secret I stay away from doctors
it's just driving it's it's tough and
the song shortly after this which I
believe is pronounced
lubes loves Loubs it's kind of odd it
drags on a little bit but the way the
bass groove works and the and the drums
are hitting at this very slow tempo and
the way the guitar leads are kind of
slithering their way into the track in
between the base and the rhythms it kind
of feels like a bluesy sort of vibe
about as bluesy as kind of a noise rock
track could be there are moments like
the closer on this LP teenage adult that
musically could be a little more
distinct could use a little bit more
maybe guitar leads or just melody or
just a weirder riff or groove to kind of
make it pop out there's just a few spots
on this LP where I feel like maybe just
a little bit more than attitude is
needed to make the song I'm listening to
great however I mean I still did not
come away from this album unsatisfied I
was very satisfied actually I'm feeling
a strong seven to a light eight on this
